# Project Summary
We are trying to address the problem that many people are incorrectly sorting their trash into different bins, leading to lots of trash in the recycling and recycling in the trash. To fix this problem we decided to use newer technology and software to try to automate the process of sorting. Using AI to detect where trash should go, and then having a system to put said trash in the right bin should remove the problem of people not sorting correctly.

# Technical Summary
This system contains 2 key parts, a machine learning model and a physical sorting implement.

The machine learning model is a variation of the Vision Transformer architecture, known as the Data Efficient Image Transformer. This was implemented in PyTorch with the 768 input features and 2 output features. The model was pretrained on the ImageNet-1k dataset, and the image normalization factors utilized the ImageNet Default Mean and ImageNet Default STD constants. The model was trained with a learning rate of 1e-6 and a weight decay of 1e-7 over a span of 1 epoch  utilizing the ADAM Gradient Descent Optimizer. The key metrics utilized to assess the model are Precision, Recall, F1-Score, and Cross Entropy Loss. The formula to calculate this are not changed from the standard in the field. The dataset to train the model is based on the [Organic vs Recycling dataset made by Sashaank Sekar](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/techsash/waste-classification-data). It contains a training and a testing dataset. The training dataset has 12.6k images of compost and 10k images of recycle. The testing dataset has 1401 compost images of compost and 1112 images of recycling. The tool “Weights and Biases” was used to plot the model metrics for both training and validaton loops over each step. The report of the model training procedure can be found [here](https://api.wandb.ai/links/artunjay/b6vmv5rc).

The physical sorting implement was designed to be a mode to dispense garbage into a trash or recycle bin. It would do so by being attached to a servo motor that would rotate to an angle of + or – 30 degrees depending on where the waste is meant to be disposed. The webcam used to classify waste is a standard computer webcam from logitech with a 1080p 24 fps capture. The prototype is made of lasercut cardboard with a final version made with wood. The computer powering this is an 8 gigabyte Raspberry Pi 4.

# Implementation Plan
We designed it to be used between every big trash recycling bin (as shown in pictures below). The current design is not able to implement the composting bin, two possible solutions  iare described  below in the next steps section. Our current system has flaws preventing immediate  deployment however. Currently, we are having issues with the Machine Learning model natively and getting it integrated onto a Raspberry Pi due to memory constraints. The current solution is to design a new, more compact model but this will take more time as the training will need to be longer. Also, the motor vibrates whenever rotating because it is overcorrecting for its movement. This is due to the weight of the platform on the motor which causes it to go further than its intention. The current solution in mind is to create PID controller to mitigate this issue.

# Next Steps
## Model Improvements
-   Redesign model to use a lower number of layers and nodes per layer to reduce overall memory consumption
    
-   Keep using the Vision Transformer architecture rather than moving to a Convolutional Neural Network for highest degree of accuracy
    
-   Aim to reach 99% or greater accuracy for a final product, current Data Efficient Image Transformer (DEIT) is at ~96%
    
-   Tune camera input size, convolutions, and framing to achieve best inputs to model in real runs
    
-   Separate classification of bottles for load sensor
    

## Sorter Improvements
    

-   Construct out of wood for final product, paint insides white for best light reflectivity and to match training data
    
-   Create PID controller for motor and see if it fixes the spasm issue of the motor (detailed at the end of the implementation plan)
    
-   Add a removable surface to the top of the platform that can either be swapped for a new one, or cleaned and replaced.
    
-   Add an elevated stand about 8-9 inches off the top of the box to mount the camera
    
-   Mount a light source inside the box
    
-   Adding load sensors to determine difference between full or empty bottles when the model classifies those.
    
-   A different angle of moving the platform, a pneumatic pusher attached onto the box, or a 2 axis rotating platform to throw compost into the correct bin.
    

## Optional Improvements for usability
    

-   A screen or buzzer that displays or makes a sound indicating what type of waste it is
    
-   A guessing system where you guess what waste it is before its thrown out
    
-   A scoreboard to see who has the most points connected via a mobile app that shows your throwing away statistics
